===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|qualm|lang=enm}}, {{term|cwalm||death, sickness, plague|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang}} {{term|cwealm|lang=ang}} {{gloss|West Saxon: "death, disaster, plague"}}, {{term|utcualm|ūtcualm|lang=ang}} {{gloss|Anglian: "utter destruction"}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{recons|kwalmaz||killing, death, destruction|lang=gem-pro}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{recons|gʷel-||to stick, pierce; pain, injury, death|lang=ine-pro}}. Related to {{term|cwelan||to die,|lang=ang}} {{term|cwellan||to kill|lang=ang}}. The other suggested etymology, less satisfying, is from {{etyl|nl}} [[kwalm]] "steam, vapor, mist," which also may be ultimately from the same Germanic root as [[quell]]. Sense softened to "feeling of faintness" 1530; meaning "uneasiness, doubt" is from 1553; that of "scruple of conscience" is 1649. An indirect connection between the Old English and modern senses is plausible, via the notion of "fit of sickness."

